				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Even though I always thought 3d polygons looked ugly until 7th generation systems, I always thought jumping from 2d to 3d was the biggest leap in video game graphics.  From researching technical specs I can also make a point that it was also the biggest leap in processor efficiency.<br /><br />Reasons:<br />- Memory was finally large enough for double buffering.<br />- Memory was finally fast enough for GPUs to fetch a single pixel at a time, allowing individual pixel manipulation, as opposed to fetching groups of several pixels at a time.<br />- CDs got rid of some of the memory constraints of cartridges.<br />- Any design flaws of 4th gen systems such as the Genesis's lack of available colors, or SNES's unflexible sprite management.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

