						<div class="postbody">Oh thank you very much guys.<br /><br />Well I don't know but 2 to 3 was probably the biggest lap, as games started to have decent graphics with multiple colours, recognizable characters and recognizable enemies. Also, games started to have storylines (even if they were cheap 99% of the time, there was games with true storylines here and there in the NES generation, such as Ninja Gaiden and so on).<br /><br />But I find there is a huge gap within the 3rd generation itself, I mean, compare Donkey Kong to Metal Slader Glory, it's quite incredible both are on the same NES, isn't it ? The former has the very early idea of recognizable character and enemies (actually the enemy gave it name to the game) while the later is a 1MB cartridge featuring large portraits of characters and probably a very complex storyline (although the game isn't translated yet).</div>

