						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tomaitheous wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I figured the 8bit attribute would just be an argument for semantics, and not what was capable or delivered (end result).</div><br />I was just guessing. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" /><br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If anything, I would say the exclusion of a separate sound processor - since the snes and genesis had those.</div><br />Could be. Maybe the lack of a second scroll plane? Many PCE/TG16 games struggled to multiple scrolling planes with parallax effects and sprites.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Golden Axe looks pretty impressive, especially compared to the NES.</div><br />Yes, but the animations are pretty stiff.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">There were a few other titles that used similar tricks (vram characters along with sprites) that looked impressive.</div><br />Mortal Kombat and Street Fighter could only have fighters that big because of this trick. Unfortunately this wasn't possible on the NES, since each tile can only use 4 colors.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Asterix and Streets of Rage look pretty impressive too.</div><br />Asterix and the Great Rescue looks the best out of all the Asterix games IMO, very impressive.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">Phantasy Star could pass as an early 16bit RPG.</div><br />The map sections look pretty crappy, but I agree the rest looks pretty good. A few games I can think of that look closer to the next generation are Donald Duck: Deep Duck Trouble, Daffy Duck in Hollywood, Chuck Rock II - Son of Chuck and Taz in Escape From Mars (this one doesn't play so smoothly though).</div>

